TypeSignature.Value: .class public interface auto ansi abstract FillFormat implements class Microsoft.Office.Core._IMsoDispObj

Docs.summary: Represents fill formatting for a shape.

remarks.para: A shape can have a solid, gradient, texture, pattern, picture, or semi-transparent fill.
Use the property to return a object.
Many of the properties of the object are read-only. To set one of these properties, you have to apply the corresponding method.

MemberSignature.Value: Public ReadOnly Property Creator As Integer
public: property int Creator { int get(); };

Docs.summary: Returns a 32-bit integer that indicates the application in which this object was created.

remarks.para: If the object was created in Microsoft Excel, this property returns the string XCEL, which is equivalent to the hexadecimal number 5843454C.
The Creator property is designed to be used in Microsoft Excel for the Macintosh, where each application has a four-character creator code. For example, Microsoft Excel has the creator code XCEL.

MemberSignature.Value: public: property float GradientAngle { float get(); void set(float value); };

Docs.summary: Gets or sets the angle of the gradient fill for the specified fill format.
Docs.value: The angle of the gradient fill for the specified fill format.

remarks.para: Read/write.

A gradient fill can be specified in the formatting for various elements (shapes) in a chart. For example, you can use the Format Data Series dialog box to format the columns in a Column chart to a gradient fill. In this case, the property corresponds to the setting of the Angle box in the Fill category of the Format Data Series dialog box. The valid range of values for the property is from 0 to 359.9.

Docs.summary: Gets an object that represents the picture or texture fill for the specified fill format.
Docs.value: Represents the picture or texture fill for the specified fill format.

remarks.para: Read-only.

A picture or texture fill can be specified in the formatting for various elements (shapes) in a chart. For example, you can use the Format Data Series dialog box to format the columns in a Column chart to a picture or texture fill. In this case, the property returns a collection that corresponds to the settings associated with the Picture or texture fill option in the Fill category of the Format Data Series dialog box.
